🔧 Quick FreeCAD Primer (for You as a Beginner)

🔹 What is FreeCAD?

  • Free, open-source 3D CAD software

  • Ideal for parametric modeling — you define dimensions using constraints

  • Popular workbenches:

    • Part Design → Build solid, parametric models (we’ll use this)

    • TechDraw → Create 2D drawings for documentation

    • Assembly4 → Connect parts into systems (optional for later)

    • Mesh Design → Export for 3D printing or simulation

🔹 Why Use FreeCAD for CubeSats?

  • You can model precise enclosures with mounting holes, solar panel bays, payload space

  • It's dimensionally constrained — easy to scale up from 1U to 3U

  • Exports to formats like .STEP, .STL, and .IGES for manufacturing or simulation

🛰️ Step-by-Step: Build a 1U CubeSat in FreeCAD

💡 Tip: Keep all dimensions in millimeters. CubeSats follow the 1U = 100 mm cube standard.

✅ Step 1: Open FreeCAD & Set Up the Environment

  1. Launch FreeCAD

  2. From the top toolbar, switch to the Part Design workbench:

    • View > Workbench > Part Design

  3. Click Create New → Save your file as cube_sat_design.FCStd

✅ Step 2: Create the CubeSat Outer Frame

  1. Click Create New Body
    → Then click Create Sketch

  2. Select the XY plane and click OK

  3. In the sketch:

    • Draw a rectangle by clicking the Rectangle tool

    • Click two opposite corners

  4. Add dimensions:

    • Select the horizontal edge → click 'Constrain Horizontal Distance' → set to 100 mm

    • Select vertical edge → 'Constrain Vertical Distance' → set to 100 mm

  5. Click Close (top-right of sketch)

  6. Now click Pad
    → Set the Length to 100 mm
    → Click OK

✅ You now have a solid 100×100×100 mm cube = 1U CubeSat!

✅ Step 3: Add a Payload Bay Inside the Cube

  1. With the same body selected, click Create New Sketch

  2. Select the top face of the cube

  3. In this new sketch:

    • Draw a smaller rectangle in the center (e.g., 60×60 mm)

    • Use constraints to center it or manually set distances

  4. Click Close

  5. Click Pocket
    → Set Depth to 80 mm
    → Click **OK`

✅ This creates an internal cavity — your payload compartment

✅ Step 4: (Optional) Add Mounting Rails or Slots

You can repeat the Sketch → Pocket method to:

  • Add internal rails (for stacking PCBs)

  • Cut side holes (for antennas, connectors)

  • Draw circles for screw holes on the side walls

✅ Step 5: Save and Export

  1. Save as cube_sat_design.FCStd

  2. Export if needed:

    • File → Export → Choose .STEP for CAD or .STL for 3D printing

🎯 What Are These Planes?

Great question — centering the second rectangle (your payload bay) is an important FreeCAD skill. Let's do it step-by-step using constraints.

🟩 GOAL:

You want to center a smaller rectangle (e.g., 60×60 mm) inside the top face of your CubeSat (100×100 mm).

✅ Step-by-Step: Center the Inner Rectangle

🧱 Step 1: Start the Second Sketch

  1. Select the top face of the CubeSat cube

  2. Click Create Sketch

  3. Select the suggested face (usually XY rotated)

  4. Draw a rectangle anywhere on the face (doesn’t need to be perfect)

✏️ Step 2: Add Horizontal & Vertical Dimensions

  1. Select the top horizontal line of the rectangle → click “Constrain Horizontal Distance” → set to 60 mm

  2. Select the left vertical line → click “Constrain Vertical Distance” → set to 60 mm

🟢 Now your rectangle is the correct size: 60×60 mm

🎯 Step 3: Center It Horizontally

  1. Select the midpoint of the top edge of the rectangle
    (Hover on the line — midpoint should show up as a white dot)

  2. Hold Ctrl and also select the Y-axis (vertical axis) — it appears as a green vertical line

  3. Click the icon for “Constrain point on object” (it looks like a dot on a line)

✅ This will align the rectangle horizontally to the center of the face.

🎯 Step 4: Center It Vertically

  1. Select the midpoint of one of the vertical edges

  2. Hold Ctrl, also select the X-axis (horizontal axis)

  3. Click “Constrain point on object” again

✅ Now your rectangle is fully centered on the face!

🧠 Summary:

  • Use “Point on Object” constraint to lock midpoint of a line to an axis

  • Make sure you've already set dimensions before centering

  • Once fully constrained, your sketch will turn green

🎯 Why Center on the Origin?

BenefitWhy It Matters
🧭 AlignmentKeeps your model symmetrical for assembly and exports
🛠 Future ConstraintsEasier to add internal parts, cutouts, and align features
🛰 Orbital ReferenceMatches world origin for simulations and 3D visualizers

✅ How to Center Your 100 mm Rectangle on the Origin

If you already drew a rectangle in your first sketch (for the outer box), here's how to center it:

🔁 Option 1: Delete and Redraw (Simplest for Beginners)

  1. Open your first sketch again

  2. Delete the current rectangle (Ctrl + A → Delete)

  3. Draw a new rectangle — place it anywhere

  4. Click one corner point, then Ctrl-click the opposite corner point

  5. Click “Constrain Symmetry” 🟰 (looks like two arrows)

  6. When it asks for the third point, click the origin dot (0,0)

✅ This makes your rectangle symmetric around the origin!

✏️ Option 2: Manually Constrain to Origin (If Already Drawn)

If you don’t want to delete:

  1. Select the midpoint of the bottom edge → Ctrl + X-axis (red)

  2. Click “Point on Object”

  3. Select the midpoint of the left edge → Ctrl + Y-axis (green)

  4. Click “Point on Object”

✅ This will snap your shape center to the origin.

Absolutely! Let’s go step by step and demystify GMAT and how you'll use it to simulate a CubeSat mission in your OpenCubeDesigner project.

🛰️ What is GMAT?

GMAT (General Mission Analysis Tool) is a powerful open-source software developed by NASA that:

  • Simulates satellite orbits and space missions

  • Visualizes trajectories in 3D

  • Calculates delta-V, eclipses, ground tracks, burns, and more

✅ It's ideal for CubeSat teams who want orbit simulation on a laptop, no expensive tools required.

🎯 What’s the Goal of cube_orbit_simulation.script?

This script is like a mission plan written in GMAT’s scripting language.
For your 1U CubeSat, the script will:

TaskPurpose
Define a satelliteIts mass, orbit, and start time
Add environmental forcesDrag, radiation pressure
Propagate orbitSimulate motion over 7 days
Show results3D orbit, ground track, ephemeris

📁 Where to Find It

kotlin
OpenCubeDesigner/
└── gmat/
    └── cube_orbit_simulation.script   ✅ (this file)

You’ll open this file in GMAT and run the simulation.

🧰 Step-by-Step Explanation of the Script

Here’s the basic script broken down with comments:

gmat
%----------------------------------------
% Define the spacecraft
%----------------------------------------
Create Spacecraft CubeSat;
CubeSat.DateFormat = UTCGregorian;
CubeSat.Epoch = '01 Jan 2025 00:00:00.000';  % Starting time
CubeSat.OrbitColor = Red;

% Position (km) and velocity (km/s) in Earth-centered inertial frame
CubeSat.X = 7000;
CubeSat.Y = 0;
CubeSat.Z = 0;
CubeSat.VX = 0;
CubeSat.VY = 7.5;
CubeSat.VZ = 0;

CubeSat.DryMass = 4;  % in kg, typical 1U CubeSat

🧠 This defines a basic CubeSat in Low Earth Orbit (~500 km).

gmat
%----------------------------------------
% Define the force model
%----------------------------------------
Create ForceModel EarthForces;
EarthForces.CentralBody = Earth;
EarthForces.SRP = On;    % Solar radiation pressure
EarthForces.Drag = On;   % Atmospheric drag

🌍 This includes environmental effects (important for small satellites).

gmat
%----------------------------------------
% Propagator Setup
%----------------------------------------
Create Propagator PropLEO;
PropLEO.FM = EarthForces;
PropLEO.Type = RungeKutta89;
PropLEO.InitialStepSize = 60;  % seconds

⚙️ This defines how to numerically integrate the orbit.

gmat
%----------------------------------------
% Mission Sequence
%----------------------------------------
BeginMissionSequence;
Propagate PropLEO(CubeSat) {CubeSat.ElapsedDays = 7};

▶️ This runs the simulation for 7 days, using the propagator above.

👀 What Will GMAT Show?

Once you run this:

  • A 3D Earth with your satellite orbit

  • A plot of altitude vs time

  • A ground track (path on Earth)

You can also export .csv ephemeris for Python or Jupyter analysis.

<script>
function generateScript() {
  const mode = document.getElementById('orbitMode').value;

  let orbitBlock = "";
  if (mode === "LEO") {
    orbitBlock = `CubeSat.SMA = 6878;\nCubeSat.ECC = 0;\nCubeSat.INC = 51.6;\n`;
  } else if (mode === "SSO") {
    orbitBlock = `CubeSat.SMA = 7078;\nCubeSat.ECC = 0;\nCubeSat.INC = 98.6;\n`;
  } else if (mode === "ELLIPTICAL") {
    orbitBlock = `CubeSat.SMA = 8000;\nCubeSat.ECC = 0.2;\nCubeSat.INC = 63.4;\n`;
  }

  const script = `Create Spacecraft CubeSat;
CubeSat.DateFormat = UTCGregorian;
CubeSat.Epoch = '01 Jan 2025 00:00:00.000';
CubeSat.DryMass = 4;
CubeSat.Cd = 2.2;
CubeSat.Cr = 1.8;
CubeSat.DragArea = 0.01;
CubeSat.SRPArea = 0.01;
CubeSat.OrbitColor = Red;

${orbitBlock}CubeSat.RAAN = 0;
CubeSat.AOP = 0;
CubeSat.TA = 0;

Create ForceModel EarthForces;
EarthForces.CentralBody = Earth;
EarthForces.PrimaryBodies = {Earth};
EarthForces.SRP = On;
EarthForces.Drag = On;

Create Propagator Prop;
Prop.FM = EarthForces;
Prop.Type = RungeKutta89;
Prop.InitialStepSize = 60;

BeginMissionSequence;
Propagate Prop(CubeSat) {CubeSat.ElapsedDays = 7};
`;

  const blob = new Blob([script], { type: 'text/plain' });
  const url = URL.createObjectURL(blob);
  const link = document.getElementById('downloadLink');
  link.href = url;
  link.style.display = 'inline';
}
</script>

Excellent question.

You're right to ask — why show a GMAT .script file to users at all?

🎯 Purpose of Showing the Script (When It Does Make Sense)

Showing the GMAT script adds value when your audience includes:

1. Educators / Students

  • They want to learn orbital mechanics

  • Seeing the script shows the “math behind the simulation”

  • It builds transparency: "This is what the simulator is running under the hood"

2. Engineers / Open-source contributors

  • May want to copy and modify the script

  • They use GMAT locally to test propulsion, burns, mission events

  • Useful for debugging or versioning

3. Toolkits like OpenCubeDesigner

  • Since you're building an open, laptop-based toolkit — showing the script supports editable, inspectable simulations

❌ When You Don't Need to Show It

If your audience is:

  • General public, just watching visualizations

  • Policymakers, clients, or investors

  • Focused more on results than process

Then you can:

  • Hide the raw script

  • Replace it with a button: “Download for GMAT”

  • Focus on visual storytelling (ground tracks, heatmaps, graphs)

✅ Middle Ground: Keep It Optional

You could include a toggle like:

html
<label>
  <input type="checkbox" onchange="toggleScript(this.checked)">
  Show underlying GMAT script
</label>

Or collapse it in an <details> tag:

html
<details>
  <summary>🔧 View GMAT Script (Advanced)</summary>
  <pre> ... script here ... </pre>
</details>

<script>
let scriptVisible = false;

function toggleScript() {
  scriptVisible = !scriptVisible;
  document.getElementById("scriptDisplay").style.display = scriptVisible ? "block" : "none";
  document.getElementById("downloadLink").style.display = scriptVisible ? "inline-block" : "none";
  updateScript();  // regenerate when toggled
}

function updateScript() {
  const mode = document.getElementById("orbitMode").value;
  let orbitParams = "";

  if (mode === "LEO") {
    orbitParams = `CubeSat.SMA = 6878;\nCubeSat.ECC = 0;\nCubeSat.INC = 51.6;`;
  } else if (mode === "SSO") {
    orbitParams = `CubeSat.SMA = 7078;\nCubeSat.ECC = 0;\nCubeSat.INC = 98.6;`;
  } else {
    orbitParams = `CubeSat.SMA = 8000;\nCubeSat.ECC = 0.2;\nCubeSat.INC = 63.4;`;
  }

  const script = `Create Spacecraft CubeSat;
CubeSat.DateFormat = UTCGregorian;
CubeSat.Epoch = '01 Jan 2025 00:00:00.000';
CubeSat.DryMass = 4;
CubeSat.Cd = 2.2;
CubeSat.Cr = 1.8;
CubeSat.DragArea = 0.01;
CubeSat.SRPArea = 0.01;
CubeSat.OrbitColor = Red;

${orbitParams}
CubeSat.RAAN = 0;
CubeSat.AOP = 0;
CubeSat.TA = 0;

Create ForceModel EarthForces;
EarthForces.CentralBody = Earth;
EarthForces.PrimaryBodies = {Earth};
EarthForces.SRP = On;
EarthForces.Drag = On;
EarthForces.AtmosphereModel = MSISE90;

Create Propagator PropLEO;
PropLEO.FM = EarthForces;
PropLEO.Type = RungeKutta89;
PropLEO.InitialStepSize = 60;

BeginMissionSequence;
Propagate PropLEO(CubeSat) {CubeSat.ElapsedDays = 7};`;

  if (scriptVisible) {
    document.getElementById("scriptDisplay").textContent = script;
    const blob = new Blob([script], { type: 'text/plain' });
    const url = URL.createObjectURL(blob);
    document.getElementById("downloadLink").href = url;
  }
}

document.addEventListener("DOMContentLoaded", updateScript);
</script>

<h2>📘 Understanding Orbit Types</h2>

<ul>
  <li><strong>LEO (Low Earth Orbit)</strong>: ~500–600 km above Earth, fast orbits (~90 min). Great for imaging and quick comms.</li>
  <li><strong>SSO (Sun-Synchronous Orbit)</strong>: A special polar orbit (~700 km) that passes over the same part of Earth at the same local solar time—ideal for Earth observation.</li>
  <li><strong>Elliptical (Molniya-type)</strong>: Highly elliptical with long dwell time over high latitudes (e.g. Russia, Canada). Useful for regional coverage.</li>
</ul>

<h2>🧪 How the Simulation Works</h2>
<p>This GMAT script simulates the CubeSat's orbit using the following:</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>SMA (Semi-Major Axis)</strong>: Determines the orbit size (~Earth radius + altitude)</li>
  <li><strong>ECC (Eccentricity)</strong>: 0 = circular, >0 = elliptical</li>
  <li><strong>INC (Inclination)</strong>: 0° = equatorial, 90° = polar, >90° = retrograde</li>
  <li><strong>RAAN, AOP, TA</strong>: Angles defining orbit orientation and position</li>
  <li><strong>Force Models</strong>: Drag, solar radiation pressure, and gravity field are included</li>
</ul>

<p>
This lets you test orbital behavior for different missions, like Earth observation, tech demos, or regional coverage.
</p>
